# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pneumatic-actuators
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] An **air compressor** is a machine that takes ambient air from the surroundings and discharges it at a higher pressure.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] It is an application of a gas compressor and a pneumatic device that converts mechanical power (from an electric motor, diesel or gasoline engine, etc.) into potential energy stored in compressed air, which has many uses.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] A common application is to compress air into a storage tank, for immediate or later use.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] When the delivery pressure reaches its set upper limit, the compressor is shut off, or the excess air is released through an overpressure valve.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The compressed air is stored in the tank until it is needed.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The pressure energy provided by the compressed air can be used for a variety of applications such as pneumatic tools as it is released.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] When tank pressure reaches its lower limit, the air compressor turns on again and re-pressurizes the tank.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] A compressor is different from a pump because it works on a gas, while pumps work on a liquid.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] There are numerous methods of air compression, divided into either positive-displacement or roto-dynamic types.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Positive-displacement compressors work by forcing air through a chamber whose volume is decreased to compress the air.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Once the pressure is greater than the pressure outside the discharge valve, a port or valve opens and air is discharged into the outlet system from the compression chamber.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The capacities for both single-stage and two-stage compressors are generally specified in Standard Cubic feet per Minute (SCFM) or litres per minute and pounds per square Inch (PSI) or bar.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] To a lesser extent, some compressors are rated in actual cubic feet per minute (ACFM).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Still others are rated in cubic feet per minute (CFM).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Using CFM alone to rate a compressor is ambiguous because it represents a flow rate without a pressure reference. i.e.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Single stage compressors usually fall into the fractional through 5 horsepower range.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Two-stage compressors normally fall into the 5 through 30 horsepower range.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Roto-dynamic air compressors include centrifugal compressors where Rotating vanes impart kinetic energy to a gas and stationary passages convert velocity into a rise in pressure, and axial compressors, where rotor blades impart the kinetic energy and stator blades convert it to a rise in pressure.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Due to adiabatic heating, air compressors require some method of disposing of waste heat.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Generally this is some form of air- or water-cooling, although some (particularly rotary type) compressors may be cooled by oil (that is then in turn air- or water-cooled).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The atmospheric changes are also considered during cooling of compressors.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The type of cooling is determined by considering the factors such as inlet temperature, ambient temperature, power of the compressor and area of application.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] There is no single type of compressor that could be used for any application.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Air compressors are also widely used in oil and gas, mining and drilling applications as the flushing medium, aerating muds in underbalanced drilling and in air pigging of pipelines.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Most air compressors either are reciprocating piston type, rotary vane or rotary screw.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Centrifugal compressors are common in very large applications, while rotary screw, scroll, and reciprocating air compressors are favoured for small and medium-sized applications.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Air compressors are designed to utilize a variety of power sources.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] While direct drive gasoline or diesel-engines and electric motors are among the most popular, air compressors that utilize vehicle engines, power-take-off, or hydraulic ports are also commonly used in mobile applications.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The power of a compressor is measured in HP (horsepower) and CFM (cubic feet per minute of intake air).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The volume of the pressure vessel and the stored pressure indicate the volume of compressed air (in reserve) available.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Gasoline and diesel-powered compressors are widely used in remote areas with problematic access to electricity.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] They are noisy and require ventilation for exhaust gases, particularly if the compressed air is to be used for a breathing air supply.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Electric-powered compressors are widely used in production, workshops and garages with permanent access to electricity.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Common workshop/garage compressors are 110-120 Volt or 230-240 Volt.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Compressor tank shapes are: "pancake", "twin tank", "horizontal", and "vertical".
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Depending on a size and purpose compressors can be stationary or portable.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] To ensure all compressor types run efficiently with no leaks, it is necessary to perform routine maintenance.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The cost of maintenance only accounts for 8% of the life cycle cost of owning an air compressor.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] According to CAGI air compressor performance verification data sheets, the higher the isentropic efficiency is, the better the energy saving is.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] The better air compressor isentropic efficiency has reached 95%.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/air-compressor] Approximately 70~80% of the air compressor's total lifetime cost is energy consumption, so using the high-efficiency air compressor is one of the energy-saving methods.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Compressed air is used as a breathing gas by underwater divers.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] The diver may carry it in a high-pressure diving cylinder, or supplied from the surface at lower pressure through an air line or diver's umbilical.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Similar arrangements are used in breathing apparatus used by firefighters, mine rescue workers and industrial workers in hazardous atmospheres.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] In Europe, 10 percent of all industrial electricity consumption is to produce compressed air—amounting to 80 terawatt hours consumption per year.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Industrial use of piped compressed air for power transmission was developed in the mid-19th century; unlike steam, compressed air could be piped for long distances without losing pressure due to condensation.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] An early major application of compressed air was in the drilling of the Mont Cenis Tunnel in Italy and France in 1861, where a 600 kPa (87 psi) compressed air plant provided power to pneumatic drills, increasing productivity greatly over previous manual drilling methods.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Compressed-air drills were applied at mines in the United States in the 1870s.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] George Westinghouse invented air brakes for trains starting in 1869; these brakes considerably improved the safety of rail operations.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] In the 19th century, Paris had a system of pipes installed for municipal distribution of compressed air to power machines and to operate generators for lighting.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Early air compressors were steam-driven, but in certain locations a trompe could directly obtain compressed air from the force of falling water.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Air for breathing may be stored at high pressure and gradually released when needed, as in scuba diving and self-contained breathing apparatus (SCBA) or used by firefighters and industrial workers, or produced continuously to meet requirements, as in surface-supplied diving.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Air for breathing must be free of oil and other contaminants; carbon monoxide, for example, in trace volumetric fractions that might not be dangerous at normal atmospheric pressure may have deadly effects when breathing pressurized air due to proportionally higher partial pressure.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Air compressors, filters, and supply systems intended for breathing air are not generally also used for pneumatic tools or other purposes, as air quality requirements differ.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Workers constructing the foundations of bridges or other structures may be working in a pressurized enclosure called a caisson, where water is prevented from entering the open bottom of the enclosure by filling it with air under pressure.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] It was known as early as the 17th century that workers in diving bells experienced shortness of breath and risked asphyxia, relieved by the release of fresh air into the bell.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Such workers also experienced pain and other symptoms when returning to the surface, as the pressure was relieved.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Denis Papin suggested in 1691 that the working time in a diving bell could be extended if fresh air from the surface was continually forced under pressure into the bell.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] By the 19th century, caissons were regularly used in civil construction, but workers experienced serious, sometimes fatal, symptoms on returning to the surface, a syndrome called caisson disease or decompression sickness.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Many workers were killed by the disease on projects such as the Brooklyn Bridge and the Eads Bridge and it was not until the 1890s that it was understood that workers had to decompress slowly, to prevent the formation of dangerous bubbles in tissues.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Air under moderately high pressure, such as is used when diving below about 20 metres (70 ft), has an increasing narcotic effect on the nervous system.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Nitrogen narcosis is a hazard when diving.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] For diving much beyond 30 metres (100 ft), it is less safe to use air alone and special breathing mixes containing helium are often used.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] In land-based applications, SCBAs, UEBSS (USA), and EBBS (EU) provide breathable air for emergency responders, industrial workers, and military personnel in hazardous environments.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] These devices use compressed air cylinders to supply clean air to the wearer, ensuring safety in oxygen-deficient or contaminated atmospheres.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] To enhance operational safety and efficiency, Kee Connections Buddy Breather coupling allows users to share air in emergency situations.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] This coupling system enables firefighters or other SCBA users to connect their breathing apparatuses, providing life-saving air support when needed.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Such innovations help improve survivability and teamwork in high-risk conditions.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] In industry, compressed air is so widely used that it is often regarded as the fourth utility, after electricity, natural gas and water.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] However, compressed air is more expensive than the other three utilities when evaluated on a per unit energy delivered basis.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Regarding operating costs, it is important to consider that compressed air represents a significant portion of total energy costs.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Roughly, every 1 kW of power produced requires 8 kW of electrical power.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Compressor rooms must be designed with ventilation systems to remove waste heat produced by the compressors.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] When air at atmospheric pressure is compressed, it contains much more water vapor than the high-pressure air can hold.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Relative humidity is governed by the properties of water and is not affected by air pressure.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] After compressed air cools, then the vaporized water turns to liquefied water.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Cooling the air as it leaves the compressor will take most of the moisture out before it gets into the piping.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Aftercooler, storage tanks, etc. can help the compressed air cool to 40 °C (104 °F); two-thirds of the water then turns to liquid.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Management of the excessive moisture is a requirement of a compressed air distribution system.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] System designers must ensure that piping maintains a slope, to prevent accumulation of moisture in low parts of the piping system.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Drain valves may be installed at multiple points of a large system to allow trapped water to be blown out.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Taps from piping headers may be arranged at the tops of pipes, so that moisture is not carried over into piping branches feeding equipment.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/compressed-air] Piping sizes are selected to avoid excessive energy loss in the piping system due to excess velocity in straight pipes at times of peak demand, or due to turbulence at pipe fittings.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] A **control valve** is a valve used to control fluid flow by varying the size of the flow passage as directed by a signal from a controller.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] This enables the direct control of flow rate and the consequential control of process quantities such as pressure, temperature, and liquid level.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] In automatic control terminology, a control valve is termed a "final control element".
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The opening or closing of automatic control valves is usually done by electrical, hydraulic or pneumatic actuators.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Normally with a modulating valve, which can be set to any position between fully open and fully closed, valve positioners are used to ensure the valve attains the desired degree of opening.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Air-actuated valves are commonly used because of their simplicity, as they only require a compressed air supply, whereas electrically operated valves require additional cabling and switch gear, and hydraulically actuated valves required high pressure supply and return lines for the hydraulic fluid.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The pneumatic control signals are traditionally based on a pressure range of 3–15 psi (0.2–1.0 bar), or more commonly now, an electrical signal of 4-20mA for industry, or 0–10 V for HVAC systems.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Electrical control now often includes a "Smart" communication signal superimposed on the 4–20 mA control current, such that the health and verification of the valve position can be signalled back to the controller.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The HART, Fieldbus Foundation, Profinet, and Profibus are the most common protocols.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The modes of failure operation are requirements of the failure to safety process control specification of the plant.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] In the case of cooling water it may be to fail open, and the case of delivering a chemical it may be to fail closed.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The fundamental function of a positioner is to deliver pressurized air to the valve actuator, such that the position of the valve stem or shaft corresponds to the set point from the control system.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Positioners are typically used when a valve requires throttling action.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] A positioner requires position feedback from the valve stem or shaft and delivers pneumatic pressure to the actuator to open and close the valve.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The positioner must be mounted on or near the control valve assembly.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] There are three main categories of positioners, depending on the type of control signal, the diagnostic capability, and the communication protocol: pneumatic, analog, and digital.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Processing units may use pneumatic pressure signaling as the control set point to the control valves.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Pressure is typically modulated between 20.7 and 103 kPa (3 to 15 psig) to move the valve from 0 to 100% position.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] In a common pneumatic positioner, the position of the valve stem or shaft is compared with the position of a bellows that receives the pneumatic control signal.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] When the input signal increases, the bellows expands and moves a beam.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The beam pivots about an input axis, which moves a flapper closer to the nozzle.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The nozzle pressure increases, which increases the output pressure to the actuator through a pneumatic amplifier relay.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The increased output pressure to the actuator causes the valve stem to move.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Stem movement is fed back to the beam by means of a cam.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] As the cam rotates, the beam pivots about the feedback axis to move the flapper slightly away from the nozzle.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The nozzle pressure decreases and reduces the output pressure to the actuator.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Stem movement continues, backing the flapper away from the nozzle until equilibrium is reached.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] When the input signal decreases, the bellows contracts (aided by an internal range spring) and the beam pivots about the input axis to move the flapper away from the nozzle.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Nozzle decreases and the relay permits the release of diaphragm casing pressure to the atmosphere, which allows the actuator stem to move upward.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Through the cam, stem movement is fed back to the beam to reposition the flapper closer to the nozzle.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] When equilibrium conditions are obtained, stem movement stops and the flapper is positioned to prevent any further decrease in actuator pressure.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The second type of positioner is an analog I/P positioner.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Most modern processing units use a 4 to 20 mA DC signal to modulate the control valves.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] This introduces electronics into the positioner design and requires that the positioner convert the electronic current signal into a pneumatic pressure signal (current-to-pneumatic or I/P).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] In a typical analog I/P positioner, the converter receives a DC input signal and provides a proportional pneumatic output signal through a nozzle/flapper arrangement.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The pneumatic output signal provides the input signal to the pneumatic positioner.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] While pneumatic positioners and analog I/P positioners provide basic valve position control, digital valve controllers add another dimension to positioner capabilities.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] This type of positioner is a microprocessor-based instrument.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The microprocessor enables diagnostics and two-way communication to simplify setup and troubleshooting.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] In a typical digital valve controller, the control signal is read by the microprocessor, processed by a digital algorithm, and converted into a drive current signal to the I/P converter.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The microprocessor performs the position control algorithm rather than a mechanical beam, cam, and flapper assembly.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] As the control signal increases, the drive signal to the I/P converter increases, increasing the output pressure from the I/P converter.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] This pressure is routed to a pneumatic amplifier relay and provides two output pressures to the actuator.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Double-acting actuators use both outputs, whereas single-acting actuators use only one output.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The changing output pressure causes the actuator stem or shaft to move.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Valve position is fed back to the microprocessor.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The stem continues to move until the correct position is attained.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] At this point, the microprocessor stabilizes the drive signal to the I/P converter until equilibrium is obtained.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] In addition to the function of controlling the position of the valve, a digital valve controller has two additional capabilities: diagnostics and two-way digital communication.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Widely used communication protocols include HART, FOUNDATION fieldbus, and PROFIBUS.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Control valves are classified by attributes and features.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] A wide variety of valve types and control operation exist.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] However, there are two main forms of action, the sliding stem and the rotary.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] The most common and versatile types of control valves are sliding-stem globe, V-notch ball, butterfly and angle types.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/control-valve] Their popularity derives from rugged construction and the many options available that make them suitable for a variety of process applications.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] A **pneumatic control valve actuator** converts energy (typically in the form of compressed air) into mechanical motion.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] The motion can be rotary or linear, depending on the type of actuator.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] A pneumatic actuator mainly consists of a piston or a diaphragm which develops the motive power.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] It keeps the air in the upper portion of the cylinder, allowing air pressure to force the diaphragm or piston to move the valve stem or rotate the valve control element.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] Valves require little pressure to operate and usually double or *triple* the input force.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] The larger the size of the piston, the larger the output pressure can be.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] Having a larger piston can also be good if the air supply is low, allowing the same forces with less input.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] These pressures are large enough to crush objects in the pipe.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] On 100 kPa input, you could lift a small car (upwards of 1,000 lbs) easily, and this is only a basic, small pneumatic valve.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] However, the resulting forces required of the stem would be too great and cause the valve stem to fail.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] This pressure is transferred to the valve stem, which is connected to either the valve plug (see plug valve), butterfly valve etc.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] Larger forces are required in high pressure or high flow pipelines to allow the valve to overcome these forces, and allow it to move the valves moving parts to control the material flowing inside.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] The valve's input is the "control signal." This can come from a variety of measuring devices, and each different pressure is a different set point for a valve.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] A typical standard signal is 20–100 kPa.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] For example, a valve could be controlling the pressure in a vessel that has a constant out-flow, and a varied in-flow (varied by the actuator and valve).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] A pressure transmitter will monitor the pressure in the vessel and transmit a signal from 20–100 kPa.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-actuator] 20 kPa means there is no pressure, 100 kPa means there is full range pressure (can be varied by the transmitters calibration points).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Like in a hydraulic cylinder, something forces a piston to move in the desired direction.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] The piston is a disc or cylinder, and the piston rod transfers the force it develops to the object to be moved.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Engineers sometimes prefer to use pneumatics because they are quieter, cleaner, and do not require large amounts of space for fluid storage.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Because the operating fluid is a gas, leakage from a pneumatic cylinder will not drip out and contaminate the surroundings, making pneumatics more desirable where cleanliness is a requirement.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] For example, in the mechanical puppets of the Disney Tiki Room, pneumatics are used to prevent fluid from dripping onto people below the puppets.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Once actuated, compressed air enters into the tube at one end of the piston and imparts force on the piston.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Consequently, the piston becomes displaced.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Pneumatic systems are often found in settings where even rare and brief system failure is unacceptable.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] In such situations, locks can sometimes serve as a safety mechanism in case of loss of air supply (or its pressure falling) and, thus remedy or abate any damage arising in such a situation.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Leakage of air from the input or output reduces the output pressure.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Although pneumatic cylinders will vary in appearance, size and function, they generally fall into one of the specific categories shown below.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] However, there are also numerous other types of pneumatic cylinder available, many of which are designed to fulfill specific and specialized functions.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] A single-acting cylinder (SAC) has one port, which allows compressed air to enter and for the rod to move in one direction only.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] The high pressure of the compressed air causes the rod to extend as the cylinder chamber continues to fill.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] When the compressed air leaves the cylinder through the same port the rod is returned to its original position.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Double-acting cylinders (DAC) use the force of air to move in both extend and retract strokes.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] They have two ports to allow air in, one for outstroke and one for instroke.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Stroke length for this design is not limited, however, the piston rod is more vulnerable to buckling and bending.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Additional calculations should be performed as well.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Telescoping cylinders, also known as telescopic cylinders can be either single or double-acting.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] The telescoping cylinder incorporates a piston rod nested within a series of hollow stages of increasing diameter.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Upon actuation, the piston rod and each succeeding stage "telescopes" out as a segmented piston.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] The main benefit of this design is the allowance for a notably longer stroke than would be achieved with a single-stage cylinder of the same collapsed (retracted) length.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] One cited drawback to telescoping cylinders is the increased potential for piston flexion due to the segmented piston design.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Consequently, telescoping cylinders are primarily utilized in applications where the piston bears minimal side loading.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Rodless cylinders have no rod, only a relatively long piston.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Cable cylinders retain openings at one or both ends, but pass a flexible cable rather than a rod.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] This cable has a smooth plastic jacket for sealing purposes.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] A single cable has to be kept in tension.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Other rodless cylinders close off both ends, coupling the piston either magnetically or mechanically to an actuator that runs along the outside of the cylinder.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] In the magnetic type, the cylinder is thin-walled and of a non-magnetic material, the cylinder is a powerful magnet, and pulls along a magnetic traveller on the outside.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] In the mechanical type, part of the cylinder extends to the outside through a slot cut down the length of the cylinder.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] The slot is then sealed by flexible metal sealing bands on the inside (to prevent gas escape) and outside (to prevent contamination).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] The piston itself has two end seals, and between them, camming surfaces to "peel off" the seals ahead of the projecting linkage and to replace them behind.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] The interior of the piston, then, is at atmospheric pressure.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] One well-known application of the mechanical type (albeit steam-powered) are the catapults used on many modern aircraft carriers.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Upon job specification, the material may be chosen.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Material range from nickel-plated brass to aluminum, and even steel and stainless steel.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Depending on the level of loads, humidity, temperature, and stroke lengths specified, the appropriate material may be selected.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Air cylinders are available in a variety of sizes and can typically range from a small 2.5 mm (1⁄10 in) air cylinder, which might be used for picking up a small transistor or other electronic component, to 400 mm (16 in) diameter air cylinders which would impart enough force to lift a car.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Some pneumatic cylinders reach 1,000 mm (39 in) in diameter, and are used in place of hydraulic cylinders for special circumstances where leaking hydraulic oil could impose an extreme hazard.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Due to the forces acting on the cylinder, the piston rod is the most stressed component and has to be designed to withstand high amounts of bending, tensile and compressive forces.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Depending on how long the piston rod is, stresses can be calculated differently.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] If the rods length is less than 10 times the diameter, then it may be treated as a rigid body which has compressive or tensile forces acting on it.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] However, if the length of the rod exceeds the 10 times the value of the diameter, then the rod needs to be treated as a column and buckling needs to be calculated as well.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Although the diameter of the piston and the force exerted by a cylinder are related, they are not directly proportional to one another.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Additionally, the typical mathematical relationship between the two assumes that the air supply does not become saturated.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Due to the effective cross sectional area reduced by the area of the piston rod, the instroke force is less than the outstroke force when both are powered pneumatically and by same supply of compressed gas.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] Using the distributed load equation provided the $A_{e}$ can be replaced with area of the piston surface where the pressure is acting on.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] On instroke, the same relationship between force exerted, pressure and *effective cross sectional area* applies as discussed above for outstroke.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] However, since the cross sectional area is less than the piston area the relationship between force, pressure and *radius* is different.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatic-cylinder] The calculation isn't more complicated though, since the effective cross sectional area is merely that of the piston surface minus the cross sectional area of the piston rod.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Pneumatic systems used in industry are commonly powered by compressed air or compressed inert gases.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] A centrally located and electrically powered compressor powers cylinders, air motors, pneumatic actuators, and other pneumatic devices.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] A pneumatic system controlled through manual or automatic solenoid valves is selected when it provides a lower cost, more flexible, or safer alternative to electric motors, and hydraulic actuators.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Pneumatics also has applications in dentistry, construction, mining, and other areas.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Although the early history of pneumatics is somewhat unclear, blowguns are often considered the earliest pneumatic device, being created independently by various indigenous groups around the world.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Bellows are an early form of air compressor used primarily for smelting and forging.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] In the first century BC, the ancient Greek mathematician Hero of Alexandria compiled recipes for dozens of contraptions in his work *Pneumatics*.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] It has been speculated that much of this work can be attributed to Ctesibius.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] The pneumatic experiments described in these ancient documents later inspired the Renaissance inventors of the thermoscope and the air thermometer, devices which relied upon the heating and cooling of air to move a column of water up and down a tube.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] German physicist Otto von Guericke (1602–1686) invented the vacuum pump, a device that can draw out air or gas from the attached vessel.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] He demonstrated the vacuum pump to separate the pairs of copper hemispheres using air pressures.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Pneumatic systems in fixed installations, such as factories, use compressed air because a sustainable supply can be made by compressing atmospheric air.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] The air usually has moisture removed, and a small quantity of oil is added at the compressor to prevent corrosion and lubricate mechanical components.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Factory-plumbed pneumatic-power users need not worry about poisonous leakage, as the gas is usually just air.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Any compressed gas other than air is an asphyxiation hazard—including nitrogen, which makes up 78% of air.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] 21% of air) would not asphyxiate, but is not used in pneumatically powered devices because it is a fire hazard, more expensive, and offers no performance advantage over air.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Smaller or stand-alone systems can use other compressed gases that present an asphyxiation hazard, such as nitrogen—often referred to as OFN (oxygen-free nitrogen) when supplied in cylinders.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Carbon dioxide is an asphyxiant and can be a freezing hazard if vented improperly.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Both pneumatics and hydraulics are applications of fluid power.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Pneumatics uses an easily compressible gas such as air or a suitable pure gas—while hydraulics uses relatively incompressible liquid media such as oil.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Most industrial pneumatic applications use pressures of about 80 to 100 psi (550 to 690 kPa).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Hydraulics applications commonly use from 1,000 to 5,000 psi (6.9 to 34.5 MPa), but specialized applications may exceed 50,000 psi (340 MPa).
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Pneumatic logic is a reliable and functional control method for industrial processes.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] In recent years, these systems have largely been replaced by electronic control systems in new installations because of the smaller size, lower cost, greater precision, and more powerful features of digital controls.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Pneumatic devices are still used where upgrade cost, or safety factors dominate.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] Another domain where pneumatic logic is beneficial is soft robotics.
[src:pneumatic-actuators/pneumatics] By introducing simpler pneumatic logic components into soft robotics, expensive, rigid components can be replaced or reduced, lowering the manufacturing costs of the construction of soft robotic systems.
